<div class="panel-pane pane-entity-field pane-node-field-fb-title"  >
  
      
  
  <div class="field field-name-field-fb-title field-type-text field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><h1>NEJM says US leaders should lose their jobs over handling of COVID-19 pandemic</h1></div></div></div>
  
  </div>
<div class="panel-pane pane-entity-field pane-node-body"  >
  
      
  
  <div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><p>In an unprecedented move,&nbsp;the editors of the New England Journal of Medicine published an editorial on October 8 heavily criticising the US government's response to the COVID-19 pandemic, noting that the upcoming presidential election "gives us the power to render judgment" on the country's leaders.</p><p>In the editorial, the authors suggest that US leaders "have taken a crisis and turned it into a tragedy," highlighting data from the Johns Hopkins Center for Systems Science and Engineering showing that the US tops the world in COVID-19 cases and in deaths from the coronavirus, exceeding the numbers so far seen in larger countries, including China. The editors point to the death rate in the US, which is more than double that of Canada and exceeds that of Japan, whilst also being ahead of lower-middle-income countries, such as Vietnam, by a factor of almost 2000.</p><p>The authors also criticise nearly every step the US has taken to combat the pandemic, noting that while the absolute numbers of tests have substantially increased, the number of tests performed per infected person puts the country below others such as Kazakhstan, Zimbabwe and Ethiopia. The editors say that although the US government has "appropriately invested heavily" in vaccine development, its "rhetoric has politicised the development process and led to growing public distrust."</p><p>Further, the NEJM editors criticise "dramatic" testing and policy failures at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), whilst noting that the National Institutes of Health (NIH) has been excluded from "much crucial government decision making." The authors conclude "when it comes to the response to the largest public health crisis of our time, our current political leaders have demonstrated that they are dangerously incompetent. We should not abet them and enable the deaths of thousands more Americans by allowing them to keep their jobs."</p><p>Do you agree or disagree with the NEJM editorial? Have your say in the comment section.</p></div></div></div>
  
  </div>
